│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.          │
│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe transformation produces a wrong exit value for  │
│ a uniform induction with an outside use. Source returns 8, but the target     │
│ returns 7. In the vectorized IR, the middle.block selects %3 from             │
│ vector.body, where %3 = add i32 %step.2, %0 and %0 is the current index. At   │
│ the last vector iteration with VF=2, index=6, so %3=7, while the correct exit │
│ is 8. The exit value must correspond to the last processed lane's             │
│ post-increment, i.e., index.next or an extract of the last lane, not the      │
│ current index + step.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nScalarEvolution confirms    │
│ the loop trip is 8 and iv.next ranges up to 9 with final exit value 8. The    │
│ produced vector plan wires the exit value from the middle block to %3 (step + │
│ index), which corresponds to the first lane's next value, not the last        │
│ lane's. The first transformation identified is                                │
│ VPlanTransforms::removeDeadRecipes, but the symptom stems from the plan       │
│ wiring of exit users for inductions: addUsersInExitBlocks deliberately skips  │
│ handling induction exit values, relying on separate logic. Consequently, the  │
│ VPIRInstruction in the exit ends up using the wrong value from the vector     │
│ body (%3) without applying the “last lane” fix.\n\n3. Root Cause              │
│ Analysis:\nIn LoopVectorize.cpp:addUsersInExitBlocks, exit users are scanned  │
│ and VPIRInstructions updated. Induction exit values are currently handled     │
│ outside VPlan and addUsersInExitBlocks skips them if isOptimizableIVOrUse(V)  │
│ and predecessor is middle.block. For our uniform IV with outside use, this    │
│ skip prevents adding the necessary extract/select to use the last lane's      │
│ value. As a result, the exit phi takes the operand from the vector body (%3 = │
│ step + index), which is the first lane, yielding 7 instead of 8. The intended │
│ behavior (per comments around 8886 and elsewhere) is that induction           │
│ resume/exit values should use the last lane (or index.next for VF=2).         │
│ Therefore, either the separate induction-exit handling did not run before     │
│ this wiring, or it is insufficient for this case; in any case,                │
│ addUsersInExitBlocks must not skip fixing operands for induction exit users   │
│ when the only available value is lane-ambiguous.\n\n4. Proposed Edit          │
│ Point(s):\nEdit file llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp, lines   │
│ 9070-9104 (function addUsersInExitBlocks): remove the special-case skip for   │
│ induction exit users (isOptimizableIVOrUse) so that exit users receive an     │
│ ExtractFromEnd of the last lane by default. This ensures that for inductions  │
│ with outside uses, the middle.block feeds the correct value (last lane) to    │
│ the exit phi.\n\nConcretely, replace:\n  if (isOptimizableIVOrUse(V) &&       │
│ ExitVPBB->getSinglePredecessor() == MiddleVPBB)\n    continue;\nwith code     │
│ that marks these for fixing or directly applies the extract-from-end, i.e.,   │
│ delete the conditional continue and let the existing loop create              │
│ ExtractFromEnd for non-live-ins. The current logic already creates            │
│ ExtractFromEnd for operands coming from the middle block; removing the skip   │
│ enforces the last-lane semantics.\n\nThis change ensures VPIRInstructions     │
│ modeling LCSSA phis in the exit block get their operand adjusted to the last  │
│ lane, matching the expected exit value (8).\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy removing    │
│ the skip in addUsersInExitBlocks for induction-related exit users, we         │
│ guarantee that the exit block uses the last-lane value (or index.next),       │
│ fixing the off-by-one and aligning the vectorized IR with the scalar          │
│ semantics. This corrects %res to be 8 instead of 7 for the reproducer,        │
│ without relying on fragile external induction-exit handling paths."})         │
